              "raw": "{\n  \"title\": \"Understanding JWT Authentication\",\n  \"content\": \"JWT (JSON Web Tokens) is a compact, URL-safe means of representing claims to be transferred between two parties. In this comprehensive guide, we'll explore how JWT works, its benefits, and best practices for implementation.\\n\\n## What is JWT?\\n\\nJWT is an open standard (RFC 7519) that defines a compact and self-contained way for securely transmitting information between parties as a JSON object.\\n\\n## Why Use JWT?\\n\\n1. **Stateless**: No need to store session data on the server\\n2. **Scalable**: Easy to scale across multiple servers\\n3. **Secure**: Can be encrypted and signed\\n4. **Cross-domain**: Works across different domains\\n\\n## Best Practices\\n\\n- Use strong secrets\\n- Implement token refresh mechanism\\n- Set appropriate expiration times\\n- Never store sensitive data in JWT\\n- Use HTTPS in production\",\n  \"excerpt\": \"Learn about JWT authentication, its benefits, and best practices for secure implementation in modern web applications.\",\n  \"category\": \"technology\",\n  \"tags\": [\"jwt\", \"authentication\", \"security\", \"web-development\"],\n  \"featuredImage\": \"https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1555949963-ff9fe0c870eb?w=800\",\n  \"status\": \"draft\"\n}"
